DOCKER Fundamentals

What is Docker?
Docker is a tool that helps you:
â€¢	Package your application along with everything it needs (code, libraries, runtime, etc.)
â€¢	Into a container, which runs consistently anywhere â€“ on your laptop, server, or cloud.
Think of Docker as a virtual shipping container â€” it wraps your app and its environment into one portable unit.
Docker is an open-source platform that automates the deployment, scaling, and management of applications using containerization. Containers package an application with its dependencies (code, libraries, configurations, etc.) into a single, lightweight, portable unit that runs consistently across different environments, such as development, testing, or production.
A toolset that simplifies creating, deploying, and running containers using simple commands and configurations.
Why Do Developers Use Docker?
Without Docker:
â€¢	You say: â€œIt works on my machine!â€ ðŸ˜…
â€¢	But your teammate or the production server has different settings â†’ app breaks âŒ
With Docker:
â€¢	You bundle the same environment across all systems â†’ No surprises âœ…

Key Components of Docker
â€¢  Docker Engine:
â€¢	The core runtime that manages containers.
â€¢	Includes:
o	Docker Daemon: A background service that manages images, containers, networks, and storage.
o	REST API: Allows interaction with the daemon programmatically.
o	Docker CLI: Command-line interface for users to interact with Docker.
â€¢  Docker Images:
â€¢	Read-only templates containing the application, libraries, and dependencies.
â€¢	Built using a Dockerfile, which specifies instructions to create the image.
â€¢	Stored in registries like Docker Hub or private registries.
â€¢  Docker Containers:
â€¢	Runnable instances of Docker images.
â€¢	Isolated environments that execute applications.
â€¢	Can be started, stopped, moved, or deleted.
â€¢  Dockerfile:
â€¢	A script with instructions to build a Docker image (e.g., base image, dependencies, commands to run).
â€¢  Docker Hub/Registries:
â€¢	Repositories for storing and sharing Docker images.
â€¢	Docker Hub is the default public registry, but private registries can be used.
â€¢  Docker Compose:
â€¢	A tool for defining and running multi-container applications using a YAML file. Ex: docker-compose.yml
â€¢  Docker Networking:
â€¢	Manages communication between containers and the host or external networks.
â€¢	Types: Bridge (default), Host, Overlay (for multi-host), etc.
â€¢  Docker Volumes:
â€¢	Persistent storage for containers to store data outside their lifecycle.
â€¢	Ensures data persists even if a container is deleted.

