Real-World Example (Spring Boot App)
1.	Write your Spring Boot app.
2.	Create a Dockerfile.
3.	Build and run the image.
4.	Connect it to a Dockerized DB.
5.	Deploy anywhere â€” local, AWS, GCP, Azure, etc.


Steps and commands to set-up docker for both application and database:
â€¢	We have a Spring Boot project built with Maven or Gradle. But make sure that we have C:\Program Files\common\apache-maven-3.9.8\bin  in environmental variables as MAVEN_HOME  in system variables and also path(check mvn -v in cmd for clarification).
â€¢	By running this command in terminal at the root of the project in IDE, we can create .jar file in spring boot application. G:\Imp_Docs\sts-workspace\ appName > mvn clean package(clean-> deletes old build files, package-> compiles code and creates .jar file). If the build is successful, you'll see a message like: BUILD SUCCESS and
â€¢	This will create something like this in target folder of our application: target/ appName -0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar.
â€¢	Before dockerizing, run the jar normally in IDE(IntelliJ) to test ,by clicking options on .jar file. If it runs without errors and starts on port 8080, youâ€™re ready for Docker!
â€¢	Then through the terminal run docker-compose up --build (note: first start docker engine and then run the command.
â€¢	We could be able to see that the container and images are created/build in docker using the command.
â€¢	To remove/stop the containers, we use the command docker-compose down & to Stop and   remove all containers and volumes  docker-compose down -v
â€¢	We need to run mvn clean package whenever we make modifications in the code / db to make sure that .jar file is updated and see build is success. Now run docker-compose up --build
â€¢	To see all the logs of the container docker logs <container_name> ,
â€¢	To see which images of the containers are up and running docker-compose ps and docker ps -a to view all containers including stopped.
â€¢	To remove all unused containers -> G:\Imp_Docs\sts-workspace\springbootdocker> docker system prune  and docker rmi <image_id>  and to remove an image docker stop app db and docker rm app db
â€¢	docker network rm my-network to remove networks that are no longer needed.
â€¢	docker push <your_image_name>  is to push images to a registry like: AWS ECR, docker hub, Google Cloud Run, or Kubernetes. Ex: docker push my-username/my-app:latest and docker push my-username/my-db:pgsql
â€¢	etc., and  docker images to see what are the images there in the docker engine.








